#welcome to the export/presentation tutorial
a tutorial to explain how to export and import your slidenotes and presentations

---
## working in the cloud

as slidenote is a webapp it is not allowed to directly access your local filesystem. therefore you cannot continuosly save a file you opened localy. instead slidenotes uses two mechanisms to avoid any kind of lost data. because we know its hard to work and to redo the same work again is a bother - even if its as fast as writing a slidenote. 

so slidenotes uses the local cache of the browser and saves an encrypted copy of your code whenever you changed the slidenote. 
all 30 seconds slidenote will perform a check if the current version has changed - and if so it will save an encrypted version of the current state of the slidenote into the cloud. 
of course you can save to the cloud everytime you feel like it by simply pressing `ctrl/cmd + s` or in the cloud-menu "*save to cloud now*". 
+++layout:left
###the cloud menu
![](cloudmenu)
*click on the cloud to open the cloud menu*
+++

you can see the current status in the cloud menu button in the top left: 
- ![](cloudchanged) a point means that you are out of sync and it will save the next time it hits the 30sec timestamp. 
- ![](cloudsync) a moving circle means that it is saving right now
- ![](clouder) an x means that something went wrong while trying to save into the cloud (internet connection bad for example) - it will retry to save till it gets it right
- ![](cloudok) a check mark means that the current version you see is saved into the cloud

---
## exporting and importing slidenotes

+++layout:left
###the filemenu
![](filemenu)
*here you can export and import to your local harddrive*
+++


in the file menu you have the option to export a slidenote to save it localy to your local filesystem. you can choose between two formats: as encrypted-file (ending on .slidenote) or as unencrypted text-file (ending on .md or .txt). 
wether format you choose is up to you. of course you could export it as a text-file if you want to edit it localy with another text-editor of your choice. 

the counterpart of that is of course the import button, which serves to open a encrypted slidenote or text-file and import it into your slidenote. 

---
## when you are done - choosing a theme
now you have written your slidenote - what can you do with it? 
at first you can choose a theme you would like to use for your slidenote-code. over the playbutton in the down-left is the button to open up the themes-selection for this slidenote. 

+++layout:left

![](playbutton)
*with a click on the edit button you open the dialog to choose a theme*
+++

here you can choose between three different themes for now. *more to come*
 
the themes makes the look and feel of your presentation differ such as altering the colors and choosing fonts. in the future they may also interpret your slidenote slightly differently to produce different effects. 
choose the theme of your choice and run the presentation to see if it fits for you. 

*why not try it out right now? exit the presentation, alter the theme and continue*

---
## what to do with a finished slidenote?

there are several options what to do next:

+++inline

###just hold it
the most obvious way is to just run the slidenote when you want to hold it in a presentation. finish the slidenote even in the very minute you are being introduced to appear on stage. we donâ€™t judge

###export it
you can export your slidenote as a finished presentation to your local harddrive by saving it as an html file. you can then send the file via email, messenger or similar way of your choice to your audience

###publish it
publish your presentation on slidenotes.io to share it directly via a simple link and password you pass to your audience or use it yourself to hold the presentation. published presentations have additional features you will love

+++
---
## exporting presentation as a file

+++layout:inline
###the filemenu
![](filemenu)
*here you can export and import to your local harddrive*

+++layout
in the **file menu** you can choose to export the presentation as a **html file**.  
the editor will then bake a ready-to-use html-file of your slidenote with the current selected theme which can be opened by a browser. *images are embedded inside the html so you only have one file*. be aware that a lot of images will blow up the filesize of the export.
 
you can choose to **use encryption** inside your slidenote, which makes it easy to exchange a presentation in a secure form via email or such.
 
if you choose a html file without encryption we aim to make it even possible to open the slidenote with a browser which cant run javascript to have the most legacy support possible. for the encrypted html file javascript is needed to decrypt the content.
 
exporting as a html file has the advantage that you can alter by hand css-styles if you want to before sending it to your audience. 
+++

+++

 
 
*if you like this feature and would be interested in further developing of this (for example making it possible to also save comments back into the file to resend to you with comments) please give us a note. *

## publishing it on slidenotes.io
+++layout:left
###publish menu
![](publishmenu)
*manage your published presentations in the publish menu*
+++

if you choose to publish it on slidenotes.io the editor will save the current state of the slidenote with the chosen theme in an encrypted presentation on slidenotes.io. it will generate a randomized url through which you and your audience can access the presentation. you dont need an account on slidenotes.io to access this published presentation - only the url and the password you have chosen when publishing this slidenote. so all you need to do is to share the url and the password with your audience. 

publishing on slidenotes.io has some extended features: 
- you and your audience can comment on the presentation by slide. this is a practical way of collecting feedback to your presentation. 
- you can host presentations online by controling the presentation of your audience in a multiuser presentation
---
## collecting feedback

+++layout:right

+++node:sequence
note right of bob: here is my first draw
bob->alice:sends presentation v.1
note left of alice: great, i'll add my advices
alice->bob:enters her comments in presentation
note right of bob: thanks. 
note over bob: changes note accordingly
bob->alice: sends presentation v.2
note left of alice: looks good to me
+++

+++


it is often crucial to collect feedback to your presentation. to facilitate an easy to use and secure way for your audience or colleagues to give you feedback we installed the function to add comments to each slide of your presentation. all comments are directly encrypted inside the browser of the audience with the same password used to open the presentation.

this can be used to introduce some interesting workflows without the need for more accounts or installing additional software. 
 
as you can publish more presentations and in different versions of one slidenote this is a convenient way to collect feedback even from different sources and to alter each presentation a little bit before the export to personalize it or adapt it to the audience you whish the presentation for. 

---
## holding a presentation online

slidenote offers a good way to complete your videoconference with the ability to share live a presentation. often the videoquality of a videoconference is not enough to fit for a presentation. who does not know the lagg-problem *ah wait its still blurry, i cant read a thing...*

instead of transporting the presentation via an encoded videostream you can invite other people to join your presentation you hold right now. you open your presentation, then press the multiuser button in the presentation controls down left. slidenote will present you a url you pass to your audience. 

pass this url in the videoconference and share the password for the presentation and they will open the same presentation but without the control buttons. now whenever you change the slide so will their version of it. no more blurry text - and even better: as slidenotes uses responsive designs people can experience your presentation on any device. 

+++node:simpleflow
a: click on ![](multiuser)
a->b: dialog pops up
b:copy url ![](multiuserdialog)
b->c: send url to audience
c:hold presentation
+++

## holding live presentations securely

+++layout:left

![stay secure](staysecure)
*stay save with slidenotes*
+++



publishing on slidenote to hold a presentation in person also holds some advantages

an often overlooked problem is that when you have to publicly hold a presentation people can see (and film) what you are typing. so having the option to have a presentation with a password you made up solely for this act is great. 

no matter if you open the presentation from your computer publicly or even worse have to use a computer from there you dont need to enter any account-details or passwords apart the *one* password for the presentation itself you will hold right now. 

---
## using multiuser presentation in live presentation

+++layout:left

![multiuser presentation](share everywhere)
+++


you can use the multiuser presentation to share the same presentation between your smartphone and the computer plugged in to the proyector. 

you can stay with your smartphone in front of your audience and still control the presentation loaded in the computer back there without any technical stuff or installing things. 

was it ever that easy to hold and control your presentation at the same time?
